\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 14.} As to issue\u8205\? (1), the crucial question for the Court to consider is whether P was D's employee at the time of the accident or whether P was a sub-contractor hired by D.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 15.} As to issue\u8205\? (2), Mr\u8205\? Lee submitted that even if it were found that P was not the employee of D, D could still be liable to P for negligence if he had provided the defective and unsafe ladder for P to use because that would be an independent negligent act on the part of D, irrespective of his relationship with P.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 16.} As Mr\u8205\? Lee accepted, issue\u8205\? (3) only arises if it is found that P was in fact D's employee at the time of the accident.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 17.} In 
