\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 19.} The question of whether or not the work performed by P was performed in the capacity of an employee or as a sub-contractor of D is a question of fact.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa120\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs22 \cf1 \b \i0 \strike0 \ul0 THE WITNESSES\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 20.} I\u8205\? heard evidence from P and D.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 21.} I\u8205\? also heard evidence from D's witnesses namely, Ng\u8205\? Fun\u8205\? Yin, Ng\u8205\? Hui\u8205\? Chun, Yip\u8205\? Kwong\u8205\? Sang, Wong\u8205\? Ming\u8205\? Biu and Chao.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 22.} Chao is and was the owner of the premises at all material times.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 23.} The undisputed evidence is that for the renovation works at the premises D hired a number of sub-contractors to carry out different aspects of the renovation works.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 24.} Ng\u8205\? Fun\u8205\? Yin was the responsible person of Hang Cheong Aluminium Engineering Co which carried out the aluminium window and glass works at the premises.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 25.} Ng\u8205\? Hui\u8205\? Chun was the responsible person of Luen Yip Air-Conditioning Electric & Water Engineering Co which carried out the plumbing, electrical and air-conditioning works at the premises.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 26.} Yip\u8205\? Kwong\u8205\? Sang carried out the wooden door works at the premises.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 27.} Wong\u8205\? Ming\u8205\? Biu carried out the plastering and masonry works at the premises.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa120\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs22 \cf1 \b \i0 \strike0 \ul0 THE EVIDENCE AND FINDINGS\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 28.} The undisputed evidence is that Chao hired D to do the interior renovation works at the premises which Chao had purchased. He had previously entrusted D since about\u8205\? 1998 with a number of interior renovation projects in respect of other properties that Chao had purchased for investment. Chao was to live at the premises after the completion of the interior renovation works.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 29.} D is about 68\u8205\? years old and had retired a few years prior to 17\u8205\? July 2013 when the accident happened. On his evidence, which I accept, he had retired in about 2008. Since his retirement, D had only done renovation works for his relatives, friends and clients that he had served for a long time, like Chao. This is undisputed.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 30.} Both Chao and D said, and I accept and find, that Chao agreed to pay D a total sum of $800,000 for the renovation works at the premises. On the undisputed evidence, Chao paid D in two instalments, the first in the sum of $500,000 and the second in the sum of $300,000 upon completion.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 31.} There is no dispute that the renovation works started on or about 15\u8205\? April 2013 and was completed in July\u8205\? 2013 although it is not clear exactly when the works started. On the evidence of D, which I accept, I find that the actual works commenced around the end of April\u8205\? 2013. As D said, there was some preparation work that had to be done before the actual commencement of the works, including obtaining the approval for the commencement of the works from the management office of Braemar Hill Mansions which was required before the renovation works at the premises could be carried out.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 32.} There is a dispute of fact as to whether the renovation works had been fully completed by 17\u8205\? July 2013.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 33.} D said that there was no work required to be done on 17\u8205\? July 2013 when P fell off the ladder as the works had been fully completed on 10\u8205\? July 2013.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 34.} P, however, said that on 17\u8205\? July 2013 he was doing touch up painting work on the wall and the ceiling at the outside entrance of the premises where holes had been left when the shoe cabinet that was previously there had been removed. P said that he was instructed by D to do the touch up works there.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 35.} I\u8205\? believe P and accept his evidence that at the time of the accident on 17\u8205\? July 2013 he was doing touch up work on the wall and ceiling at the outside entrance of the premises. I\u8205\? also believe P and accept his evidence that he had been instructed by D to do the touch up work there. On this dispute of fact, I prefer the evidence of P, which I accept, to the evidence of D, which I reject. I\u8205\? accept that the renovation works had been substantially completed by 10\u8205\? July 2013, but I find that there was follow up work that was required to be done, such as touch up painting on the wall where holes had been left by the nails when the shoe cabinet had been removed from the outside entrance of the premises.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 36.} As I have said, it is P's case that he was a direct employee of D and not a sub-contractor.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 37.} P said that he first met D in 2002 and knew that he was a renovation contractor. According to P, he first worked for D as an employee on a short term basis from time to time.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 38.} P's evidence was that over the period from April to July 2013 he worked on a number of different flats for D and that he received a total sum of over $60,000 from D. P's evidence was that he was a casual worker employed by D and that D had agreed to pay him wages at $1,000 per day.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 39.} D gave evidence that P had given him a verbal quotation of $80,000 for 80\u8205\? days' work for the painting works at the premises and that he accepted P's quotation.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 40.} P also said that he did not employ any workers to assist him and that he did not and could not recruit others to complete his work. He said that his working hours were decided and arranged by D. His working hours were fixed from 9\u8205\?\u8239\?am to 6\u8205\?\u8239\?pm from Monday to Saturday and that if requested by D, he might work on a Sunday or public holiday. He also said that he was not permitted by D to work for other employers during the period that he was hired by D.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 41.} It was, however, clear on the evidence that P did not go to work every day at the premises. He also took some time off during the period of the renovation works to visit his hometown in the Mainland. However, P said that if he went to work late or left work earlier, he would have to give notice to D.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 42.} P also said that he was not responsible to bring or supply any tools or equipment for the painting work that he did at the premises as these were all supplied by D. He also said that the ladder from which he fell off on 17\u8205\? July 2013 and which he had used at the premises was supplied by P. P also said that he had been using two worn out ladders while working at the premises which had been supplied by D. He added that he had requested P to provide him with a new ladder but that D had told him that he would buy a new ladder after completion of the renovation works at the premises.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 43.} D denied emphatically that P was ever his employee. D's evidence was that as a contractor for renovation works, he would sub-contract different parts of the work to sub-contractors and supervise them to ensure the quality of the work in a timely fashion. He said that he did not need to and did not employ any workers of his own to work for him.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 44.} D said that, apart from supplying the paint to be used at the premises, he did not supply any of the tools or equipment or the ladder to P.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 45.} There is no dispute that D knew Chao for about 20\u8205\? years and had worked for him on a number of different projects. The undisputed evidence is that Chao contacted D in about April 2013 to ask him to do the renovation works at the premises. D agreed to do so. D in turn contacted and hired different sub-contractors for different parts of the renovation works. He listed the different sub-contractors in Annexure\u8205\? 1 to his witness statement which stood as his evidence in chief. On D's evidence, P was one such sub-contractor responsible for the painting works in the premises.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 46.} Apart from there being a dispute of fact as to whether P was an employee or sub-contractor, there is no dispute that the persons, other than P, mentioned in Annexure\u8205\? 1 to D's witness statement were hired by D as his sub-contractors for the renovation works. I\u8205\? so find.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 47.} D's evidence was that when he hired P he told him that he was going to sub-contract the painting works at the premises to him.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 48.} I\u8205\? would observe that in the re-examination of P when his counsel asked him whether D had said to him that he was sub-contracting the works to him, P at first said yes, but then later changed his evidence and denied that was ever said by D.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 49.} On this dispute of fact, I prefer the evidence of D, which I accept, to the evidence of P, which I reject. I\u8205\? find that D told P when hiring him that P was hired as D's sub-contractor for the painting works at the premises.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 50.} There was also another painter Wong\u8205\? Wai\u8205\? Pun ("Ah Pun") who did painting works at the premises during the period of the renovation works.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 51.} P said that Ah Pun was also an employee of D. D's evidence was that Ah Pun was not his employee but that he was employed by P as P's employee.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 52.} On this dispute of fact, I prefer the evidence of D, which I accept, to the evidence of P, which I reject.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 53.} Ah Pun would have been an important witness for P to call. Ah Pun in fact made a witness statement but P did not call him to give evidence. The explanation P gave for not calling Ah Pun to give evidence was that Ah Pun was unwilling to testify for him as he did not wish other contractors to know that he came to court to give evidence against a contractor. He said that it was possible that other contractors may not hire him in future if he testified.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 54.} The explanation given by P for not calling Ah Pun to give evidence is, in my view, unconvincing and unsatisfactory. I\u8205\? do not believe P on this matter. Ah Pun had no difficulty in making a witness statement to P's solicitors. He must have known that his witness statement would be supplied to D.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 55.} In my view, there is no satisfactory explanation given by P for not calling Ah Pun. It does not appear that P's solicitors ever issued and served a subpoena on Ah Pun for him to appear and to give evidence at trial.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 56.} In my view, an adverse inference can and should be drawn that if Ah Pun had been called to give evidence, his evidence would not have supported P's case (see the observations of Le\u8205\? Pichon JA in 
\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 Li Sau Keung v Maxcredit Engineering Ltd & Another [2004] 1 HKC 434 \par}
at 443 - 444).\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 57.} The witness Ng\u8205\? Fun\u8205\? Yin was the responsible person of Hang Cheong Aluminium Engineering Co Ltd, the sub-contractor hired by D to do the aluminium window and glass works at the premises. He has known D for over 20\u8205\? years. Ng Fun Yin's observation and understanding was that D did not employ any of the renovation workers to work at the premises. Ng\u8205\? Fun\u8205\? Yin also said that he did employ his own workers to do the works.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 58.} Ng\u8205\? Fun\u8205\? Yin said that he was paid after completion of the works and that he did not require D to make a payment to him in advance. His impression was that all the other workers were all working for sub-contractors. He said he did not receive a reward or tips or bonus for good and timely performance of the works. He said that after completion of the works he did not receive anything extra other than what was quoted.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 59.} The witness Ng\u8205\? Hui\u8205\? Chun was the sub-contractor hired by D to do the plumbing, electrical and air-conditioning works at the premises. He has known D for nearly 20\u8205\? years. It was also his impression that P did not hire any employees to do any part of the renovation works. His recollection was that he would not require payment in advance. \u8204\?Ng\u8205\? Hui\u8205\? Chun also hired his own workers to do the works at the premises that were sub-contracted to him by D.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 60.} Ng Hui Chun gave unchallenged evidence that whilst he was working at the premises he saw P sometimes arrived to work at the premises later than the usual time of 9\u8239\?am or 9:30\u8239\?am. He said that P sometimes arrived after 10\u8239\?am and sometimes even at 11\u8239\?am. He said that on occasions P also left early as he left the premises before 5\u8239\?pm. It was also his evidence that at times P did not turn up for work at the premises for more than a week.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 61.} P said that he notified D when he was going to arrive late or leave early and also when he would take leave and go back to his hometown in the Mainland. D denied this in evidence. On this dispute of fact, I prefer the evidence of D, whose evidence I believe and accept, to the evidence of P, whose evidence I disbelieve and reject.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 62.} Ng\u8205\? Hui\u8205\? Chun also gave evidence that he did receive a sum of about $2,000 from D as a bonus or tea money after completion of the sub-contracted works for good and timely performance of the works. I\u8205\? believe him.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 63.} The witness Yip\u8205\? Kwong\u8205\? Sang was the sub-contractor hired by D to do the wooden door works. He has known D for over 10\u8205\? years. It was also his impression that D did not employ any of the renovation workers to work at the premises. His impression was that P was not D's employee but a sub-contractor but he accepted that he did not actually know the relationship between P and D.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 64.} It was also Yip\u8205\? Kwong\u8205\? Sang's evidence that he did not require an advance payment for the works sub-contracted to him and that he was paid only after completion of the works.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 65.} Yip\u8205\? Kwong\u8205\? Sang also gave evidence that after completion of the sub-contracted works at the premises D did give him around $1,000 to $2,000 as tea money. This was extra money given to him by D which he said was given to him every time he finished a project for D. He said that the amount given was sometimes less and sometimes more and it ranged from about $1,000 to $2,000. I\u8205\? believe him. I\u8205\? find that Yip\u8205\? Kwong\u8205\? Sang also received from D some extra money at the completion of the sub-contracted works in the sum of around $1,000 to $2,000.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 66.} The witness Wong\u8205\? Ming\u8205\? Biu was the sub-contractor hired by D to do the plastering and masonry works at the premises. He has known D for about 20\u8205\? years. He said that he did not require advance payment from D and that he would be paid after completion of the works.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 67.} Wong\u8205\? Ming\u8205\? Biu also gave evidence that he saw P and another painter doing the painting works at the premises. His impression was that D did not employ workers to work for him but he also said that he did not actually know the relationship between P and the D.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 68.} Wong\u8205\? Ming\u8205\? Biu said that he did not receive any bonus or reward from D for good and timely performance.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 69.} Chao gave evidence that he did see P at the premises whom he knew to be the contractor doing the painting works at the premises. He had met P previously when P also worked in another property of Chao. Chao said that he provided the colour sample of the paint to D but that he did not supply the paint or the tools that was used by P for the painting works. I\u8205\? believe him and accept his evidence.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 70.} Chao also gave evidence that he saw D give an advance payment to P and some of the other sub-contractors. I\u8205\? believe him.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 71.} Although Chao could not remember the exact date when he saw D give advance payments to some of the sub-contractors, he said that he recalled that on the occasion that he saw D give P an advance payment in cash of $1,000 bills, D also paid the electrical sub-contractor and the masonry sub-contractor. The electrical sub-contractor was Ng\u8205\? Hui\u8205\? Chun and the mansonry sub-contractor was Wong\u8205\? Ming\u8205\? Biu. However, both Ng\u8205\? Hui\u8205\? Chun and Wong\u8205\? Ming\u8205\? Biu said that they did not require advance payment from D. It seems to me that Ng\u8205\? Hui\u8205\? Chun and Wong\u8205\? Ming\u8205\? Biu may be mistaken in their recollection of whether they received any advance payment. Chao was clear in his recollection of these matters. I accept and prefer his evidence to the evidence of Ng\u8205\? Hin\u8205\? Chun and Wong\u8205\? Ming\u8205\? Bun on this matter. In my view, it is unlikely that the sub-contractors would carry out the works without some advance payment being made to them.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 72.} I\u8205\? find, as a fact, that, as observed by Chao around the time when the work commenced at the premises, D did give some advance payment in cash to P although, as Chao said, he did not know whether it was a deposit payment. Chao was sure that P was paid in cash by D on that occasion but he did not know how much he was actually paid by D on that occasion. D gave evidence that he paid P the sum of $19,000 on 29\u8205\? April 2013. This was denied by P. P said that the first instalment of $20,000 was paid to him much later and only on 18\u8205\? June 2013. On this dispute of fact, I prefer the evidence of D, which I accept, to the evidence of P, which I reject. I\u8205\? believe D and disbelieve P on this matter.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 73.} I\u8205\? also bear in mind that P said that he was not paid by D daily or at regular intervals. He said that for the work that he did at the premises he was paid in two instalments by D. In re-examination, P said that the first instalment was paid to him on 18\u8205\? June 2013 when he received $20,000 from P. The second instalment was when he received $21,000 from D on 19\u8205\? July 2013. In re-examination he also said that he received a further sum of $3,000 on 19\u8205\? July 2013 from D so that he could go back to his hometown to take a rest after his discharge from hospital. That was his explanation for the total sum of $24,000 which he said he received from D on 19\u8205\? July 2013. When it was pointed out to P that in his witness statement he mentioned that he received $24,000 on 19\u8205\? July 2013 as salary, he tried to explain the discrepancy by saying that he lumped the sum of $21,000 salary and the sum of $3,000 gratuitous payment that D gave him on the same occasion. I\u8205\? would observe that he clearly said in his witness statement that the whole sum of $24,000 he received on 19\u8205\? July 2013 was the balance of the salary that he had received from P. P was evasive when giving evidence on this matter.\par}

\qj \hyphpar0 \cbpat0 {\sa60\sb60\li0\ri0\fi0\sl288\slmult1 \f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 {\f10 \fs20 \cf1 \b0 \i0 \strike0 \ul0 74.} I\u8205\? would also observe that P's evidence is that he only received the first instalment of his salary for the works at the premises on 18\u8205\? June 2013 in the sum of $20,000. In my view, it is inconceivable that, if he were truly a casual worker and an employee of D, he would have waited until 18\u8205\? June 2013 to get the first instalment of his wages bearing in mind that he started work at the premises towards the end of April\u8205\? 2013.\par}

